<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[264,1323,284,590]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,444,444,470]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Discussion</emphasis>
: The larva is very close to those of 
<taxonomicName box="[865,1027,444,469]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gorirossiae">
<emphasis box="[865,1027,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">S. gorirossiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1084,1240,444,469]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="temascalense">
<emphasis box="[1084,1240,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">temascalense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based upon similar anal sclerite and accessory plates morphology, and presence of ventrolateral papillae on the larva. However, the peculiar form and disposition of the pupal gill branches permits their separation.
</paragraph>
